<h2>
    <a href="/blog/two-dimensional-collisions/">Two-dimensional collisions</a>
</h2>




<h6 class="post-meta">
    Posted by:
    
    <a href="/blog/author/christian/">christian</a>
    
    
    
    in
    
    <a href="/blog/category/featured-on-frontpage/">Featured on frontpage</a>
    
    
    
    on 24 Jun 2019
</h6>





<a href="/blog/two-dimensional-collisions/">
    <img class="img-thumbnail pull-left" src="/static/media/uploads/blog/collision/.thumbnails/collision-img.png/collision-img-90x90.png">
</a>





<p>This small Python project is a physical simulation of two-dimensional physics. The animation is carried out using Matplotlib's <a href="https://matplotlib.org/3.1.0/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.animation.FuncAnimation.html"><code>FuncAnimation</code> method</a> and is implemented by the class <code>Simulation</code>. Each "particle" of the simulation is represented by an instance of the <code>Particle</code> class and depicted as a circle with a fixed radius which undergoes elastic collisions with other particles.</p>




<div class="blog-list-detail">
    
    
    <p>
    <a href="/blog/two-dimensional-collisions/">read more</a>
    
    /
    
    <a href="/blog/two-dimensional-collisions/#comments">
        0 comments
    </a>
    
    
    </p>
</div>






